essdate=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n|- style=\"height:42px; background:#e9e9e9;\"\n! style=\"width:90px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| TV channel\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Democratic Rally|DISY]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Progressive Party of Working People|AKEL]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Democratic Party (Cyprus)|DIKO]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Movement for Social Democracy|EDEK]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Ecological and Environmental Movement|KOP]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Solidarity Movement (Cyprus)|KA]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[Citizens' Alliance (Cyprus)|SYPOL]]\n! style=\"font-size:95%\"| [[ELAM (Cyprus)|ELAM]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#1569C7; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#B31B1B; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#FF7E00; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#164F46; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#7FFF00; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#004B91; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#9AB973; width:65px;\"|\n! style=\"background:#000000; width:65px;\"|\n|-\n| [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|CyBC]]\n| style=\"background:#C8D9EC\"| '''29.5 \u2013 32.5'''\n| 26.5 \u2013 29.5\n| 12 \u2013 14\n| 5 \u2013 7\n| 4 \u2013 5\n| 4 \u2013 7\n| 5 \u2013 7\n| 3.5 \u2013 4.5\n|-\n| [[ANT1 Cyprus|ANT1]]\n| style=\"background:#C8D9EC\"| '''29.5 \u2013 33.5'''\n| 25.5 \u2013 29.5\n| 12.5 \u2013 14.5\n| 5.3 \u2013 6.7\n| 3.3 \u2013 4.7\n| 3.8 \u2013 5.2\n| 4.5 \u2013 5.7\n| 3.5 \u2013 4.5\n|-\n| [[Mega Channel Cyprus|MEGA]]\n| style=\"background:#C8D9EC\"| '''30.5 \u2013 33.5'''\n| 26 \u2013 29\n| 11.5 \u2013 14\n| 4.5 \u2013 6.6\n| 3.5 \u2013 4.5\n| 3.5 \u2013 4.5\n| 4.5 \u2013 6.6\n| 2.5 \u2013 4.5\n|-\n| [[Sigma TV|Sigma]]\n| style=\"background:#C8D9EC\"| '''29 \u2013 34'''\n| 24 \u2013 29\n| 12 \u2013 15\n| 4 \u2013 6.5\n| 3.5 \u2013 6\n| 4.5 \u2013 7\n| 4.5 \u2013 7\n| 3 \u2013 5.5\n|}\n\n==Results==\n\n{{Cypriot legislative election, 2016}}\n\n=== Analysis and reception ===\nThe election had the lowest turnout for a legislative election in the history of the Republic of Cyprus. \"General apathy with public affairs, but likewise frustration with the credit crunch and disappointment with politicians\" was cited in the ''[[Cyprus Mail]]'' for the low turnout, whilst political analyst Hubert Faustmann cited \"dissatisfaction of the public with the bigger parties\" and \"that parliamentary elections in Cyprus are not that important, given the weakness of the Cypriot parliament\". AKEL was seen as the biggest loser of the election, possible reasons being cited as the party's failure to take up a \"proactive\" role and continued disillusionment with the Christofias administration. In contrast, an AKEL member, [[Irini Charalambidou]], gained the highest number of votes for any candidate, following her stark critique of and fight against failing banks. The results were interpreted as a weakening of the front calling for a federal solution by the Turkish Cypriot press and political analyst Louis Igoumenides. Whilst the pro-solution parties, DISY and AKEL, still received a combined 56% of the votes against 40% obtained by anti-solution parties, in the case of a referendum the \"yes\" vote was expected by Igoumenides to be much lower, partly due to the refusal of fanatic voters of DISY and AKEL to collaborate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cyprus parliamentary vote puts far-right in parliament|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cyprus-election-idUSKCN0YD0R4|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=23 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=cmail>{{cite web|last1=Hazou|first1=Elias|title=Election outcome doesn\u2019t bode well for settlement, political observer says|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2016/05/23/election-outcome-doest-bode-well-settlement-political-observer-says/|publisher=Cyprus Mail|accessdate=23 May 2016|date=23 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of economics, the Anastasiades government became dependent on smaller parties in order to pass important reforms. This was expected to impede the ability of the government to pass these reforms, economic analyst Fiona Mullen said \"I think we can forget privatization altogether\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Cyprus\u2019s Anastasiades Sees Support Cut in Parliamentary Vote|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-22/cyprus-s-anastasiades-sees-mps-cut-in-first-vote-since-bailout|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=23 May 2016}}</ref> This was also the first time the far-right party ELAM entered the parliament. Anti-racist NGO KISA called upon political parties in the parliament to counter ELAM and stated its \"concern over the number of absentee voters and the rightward drift of the electorate towards political parties that espouse racism and nationalism\" and Turkish Cypriot daily ''[[Diyalog]]'' called the party \"terrorist\".<ref>{{cite web|title=KISA calls on parties to counter ELAM|url=http://in-cyprus.com/kisa-calls-parties-counter-elam/|publisher=Cyprus Weekly|accessdate=23 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524121549/http://in-cyprus.com/kisa-calls-parties-counter-elam/|archive-date=24 May 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=cmail/>\n\nCypriot electoral expert Yiannis Mavris said: \"The electoral results herald a new political era for Cyprus. New small parties seem to be here to stay and will be exerting continuous pressure on traditional parties, which may find it difficult to win back their voters.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=News Analysis: Cypriot traditional parties count their losses in parliamentary election |agency=[[Xinhua]] |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-05/23/c_135382283.htm |date=23 May 2016 |accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Cypriot elections}}\n\n[[Category:Legislative elections in Cyprus|2016]]\n[[Category:2016 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:2016 in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2010s in Cypriot politics]]\n[[Category:May 2016 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2016 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "KnolGua", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eElectoral system", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Cypriot_legislative_election"}
