{"title_page": "Hugo Tyerman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n'''Hugo Nelson Tyerman''' (27 December 1880 \u2013 7 September 1977) was a noted British journalist and writer, described by ''[[The Times]]'' as \"the doyen of Fleet Street Educational Journalists\".\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on 27 December 1880, Hugo Tyerman was educated at [[Bedford School]], between 1889 and 1898, where his father, Nelson Rich Tyerman, a noted Victorian poet, was a master. He was named after [[Victor Hugo]], with whom Nelson Rich Tyerman regularly corresponded whilst completing some of the first English translations of Hugo's sonnets. His journalistic career began in 1898 when he joined [[Isaac Pitman|Sir Isaac Pitman and Son]], moving from there to [[Cassell (publisher)|Cassells]], and then to the [[Amalgamated Press|Harmsworth Group]] (later to become the [[Amalgamated Press]]) and commencing his long association with [[Arthur Mee]]. Tyerman was responsible for producing the highly successful ''[[My Magazine]]'' and was [[Editing|Art Editor]] of ''[[The Children's Encyclop\u00e6dia]]'', a publication which he was later to revise and update. In 1919, the first edition of ''[[The Children's Newspaper]]'', the first weekly newspaper of its kind, was published. Tyerman wrote much of the material for the publication and, upon the death of [[Arthur Mee]] in 1943, he became its editor. He remained editor until his retirement in 1952 at the age of 72.<ref>Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 22 September 1977, p.17</ref>\n\nIn 1940, [[Arthur Mee]]'s highly successful county series ''The King's England'' was first published and Tyerman wrote the volume on [[Essex]], which was the first to appear. The series was incomplete when [[Arthur Mee]] died and Tyerman was responsible for completing the works on the remaining counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thorotonsociety.org.uk/publications/articles/amanmoved.htm|title=The Thoroton Society of Nottinghamshire > Articles from the Thoroton Society Newsletter > A man moved by a child's curiosity by Alan Spooner|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHugo Tyerman was elected a [[Fellow]] of the [[Chartered Institute of Journalists]] in 1953. He died in [[Dorking]], Surrey, on 7 September 1977.<ref>Obituary, ''The Ousel'', Vol.LXXXI, No.897, November 1977, p.120</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tyerman, Hugo Nelson}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:English book editors]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n'''Hugo Nelson Tyerman''' (27 December 1880 \u2013 7 September 1977) was a noted British journalist and writer, described by ''[[The Times]]'' as \"the doyen of Fleet Street Educational Journalists\".\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on 27 December 1880, Hugo Tyerman was educated at [[Bedford School]], between 1889 and 1898, where his father, Nelson Rich Tyerman, a noted Victorian poet, was a master. He was named after [[Victor Hugo]], with whom Nelson Rich Tyerman regularly corresponded whilst completing some of the first English translations of Hugo's sonnets. His journalistic career began in 1898 when he joined [[Isaac Pitman|Sir Isaac Pitman and Son]], moving from there to [[Cassell (publisher)|Cassells]], and then to the [[Amalgamated Press|Harmsworth Group]] (later to become the [[Amalgamated Press]]) and commencing his long association with [[Arthur Mee]]. Tyerman was responsible for producing the highly successful ''[[My Magazine]]'' and was [[Editing|Art Editor]] of ''[[The Children's Encyclop\u00e6dia]]'', a publication which he was later to revise and update. In 1919, the first edition of ''[[The Children's Newspaper]]'', the first weekly newspaper of its kind, was published. Tyerman wrote much of the material for the publication and, upon the death of [[Arthur Mee]] in 1943, he became its editor. He remained editor until his retirement in 1952 at the age of 72.<ref>Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 22 September 1977, p.17</ref>\n\nIn 1940, [[Arthur Mee]]'s highly successful county series ''The King's England'' was first published and Tyerman wrote the volume on [[Essex]], which was the first to appear. The series was incomplete when [[Arthur Mee]] died and Tyerman was responsible for completing the works on the remaining counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thorotonsociety.org.uk/publications/articles/amanmoved.htm|title=The Thoroton Society of Nottinghamshire > Articles from the Thoroton Society Newsletter > A man moved by a child's curiosity by Alan Spooner|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHugo Tyerman was elected a [[Fellow]] of the [[Chartered Institute of Journalists]] in 1953. He died in [[Dorking]], Surrey, on 7 September 1977.<ref>Obituary, ''The Ousel'', Vol.LXXXI, No.897, November 1977, p.120</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tyerman, Hugo Nelson}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:English book editors]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Tyerman"}
{"title_page": "Hugo Medrano", "text_new": "{{short description|Director, playwright, and actor}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hugo Medrano\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| residence          = Washington D.C.\n| nationality        = Argentinian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Director, Playwright, Actor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Co-Founder of the Gala Hispanic Theatre\n| notable_works      = \n| spouse             = Rebecca Read Medrano\n}}\n'''Hugo Medrano''' is an [[Argentina|Argentinian]]-born theatre director, playwright, and actor.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/act-one-galas-first-29-years.html|title=ACT ONE: The First Three Decades|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> He co-founded the [[GALA Hispanic Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] with his wife Rebecca Read Medrano. The GALA Hispanic Theatre features Spanish and Latin American plays and has staged over 220 productions since its founding in 1976.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/act-two-ushering-in-new-era.html|title=ACT TWO: Ushering In A New Era|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano serves as the theatre's Founding Producing Artistic Director. Along with directing [[Latino theatre in the United States|Latino theatre]], Medrano is an accomplished actor. He received the [[Helen Hayes Award]] for Outstanding Lead Actor for his role as Molina in [[Kiss of the Spider Woman (novel)|El Beso de la Mujer Arana]] in 1994. Medrano's work with the Gala Hispanic Theatre has earned international acclaim. For his dedication to promoting Spanish culture in the [[United States]], Medrano was bestowed the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic|Order of Queen Isabella]] by [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Carlos I]], former King of [[Spain]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/hugo-medrano.html|title=Hugo Medrano|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHugo Medrano lived in Argentina for much of his early life. He attended Escuela de Teatro de La Plata and graduated with a Bachelor's degree in Theatre.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Shortly after graduation, Medrano fled [[political violence]] as a result of Argentina's [[Dirty War]] which targeted [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] political dissidents.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mdtheatreguide.com/2011/10/an-interview-with-gala-hispanic-theatres-hugo-medrano/|title=An Interview with GALA Hispanic Theatre\u2019s Hugo Medrano|last=Matema|first=ZSun-nee|date=2011-10-08|website=Maryland Theatre Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> He reported that many of his friends were some of the students, intellectuals, and artists who [[Forced disappearance#Argentina|disappeared]] as a result of the war. These experiences inspired the political themes of Medrano's early work.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nMedrano continued his studies in Spain at the [[:es:Teatro Estudio de Madrid|Teatro Estudio de Madrid]]. He lived and performed in Spain for five years before immigrating to the United States.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nHugo Medrano's career in the United States began at Teatro Doble, a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] children's theatre located in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, most of his notable work was done with the GALA Hispanic Theatre. GALA stands for Grupo de Artistas Latino Americanos.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://wamu.org/story/13/09/13/gala_hispanic_brings_spanish_language_theater_to_dc_for_nearly_40_years/|title=Gala Hispanic Brings Spanish-Language Theater To D.C. For Nearly 40 Years|website=WAMU|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano co-founded this theatre in 1976 to deliver quality plays to the growing Spanish-speaking community of Washington. In its early years, the GALA Hispanic Theatre performed in a townhouse in the multicultural [[Adams Morgan]] neighborhood of the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/blog-post/hugo-and-rebecca-medrano-and-hispanic-theater|title=Hugo and Rebecca Medrano and Hispanic Theater|date=2017-10-25|website=Wilson Center|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano produced and directed the group's first production, [[:es:La fiaca (obra de teatro)|La Fiaca]] by [[:es:Ricardo Talesnik|Ricardo Talesnik]], which received recognition by the [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]. Medrano would go on to direct, produce, and act in a multitude of successful productions over the next 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/production-history.html|title=Production History|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BxU-f08JvfaYS1BDLTZPYmRhdVE/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=Production History June 2016.pdf|website=Google Docs|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAs a theatre director at GALA, Hugo Medrano faced challenges concerning the bilingual nature of his productions. To appeal to both Spanish-speaking and English-speaking audiences, Medrano would often present two different productions of the same play, an English version and a Spanish version.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In some cases, this would require two different actors, [[Costume coordination|costumes]], or directors to perform these productions. Medrano found this approach to be inefficient, and the GALA Hispanic Theatre subsequently transitioned to producing plays in Spanish and providing English subtitles or headphone translations to the audience.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nMoving the GALA Hispanic Theatre to a permanent home in the [[Tivoli Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Tivoli Theatre]] of [[Columbia Heights, Washington, D.C.|Columbia Heights]] was an important moment in Hugo Medrano's career. The Tivoli Theatre was built in 1924 and quickly became a city landmark as both a theatre and a cinema.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/05/history-of-tivoli-theatre.html|title=The Venue - History of Tivoli Theatre|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> The theatre was abandoned in 1976 but was restored with the help of a $4 million fundraising campaign started by Hugo Medrano and others.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> In 2005, the GALA Hispanic Theatre officially moved into the Tivoli Theatre and Medrano began to work on new projects. With the help of his wife, Hugo Medrano created the National Center for Latino Performing Arts and has expanded GALA's focus to include concerts, dance, film, and other arts.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Notable productions ==\n\n===''In the Heights''===\n''[[In the Heights]]'' is a [[Tony Award]] winning broadway musical which featured music and lyrics by [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]. In 2017, Hugo Medrano and the GALA Hispanic Theatre hosted the first all Spanish version of the production in the United States. The musical is usually performed in [[Spanglish]], a mix of Spanish and English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/04/18/lin-manuel-miranda-in-the-heights-spanish-premiere-gala-theatre/|title=An All-Spanish Version of Lin-Manuel Miranda's \"In the Heights\" Has Its US Premiere at DC's GALA Hispanic Theatre|date=2017-04-18|website=Washingtonian|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nHugo Medrano was recognized as a \"Visionary\" by the Mayor's Arts Awards in 2014. He also received an Immigrant Achievement Award from the [[American Immigration Council]] in 2014. In 2010, both Hugo Medrano and his wife Rebecca Read Medrano were named Washingtonians of the Year by the [[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]] magazine.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medrano, Hugo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Argentine emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Argentine descent]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American male actors]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Director, playwright, and actor}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hugo Medrano\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| residence          = Washington D.C.\n| nationality        = Argentinian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Director, Playwright, Actor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Co-Founder of the Gala Hispanic Theatre\n| notable_works      = \n| spouse             = Rebecca Read Medrano\n}}\n'''Hugo Medrano''' is an [[Argentina|Argentinian]]-born theatre director, playwright, and actor.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/act-one-galas-first-29-years.html|title=ACT ONE: The First Three Decades|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> He co-founded the [[GALA Hispanic Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] with his wife Rebecca Read Medrano. The GALA Hispanic Theatre features Spanish and Latin American plays and has staged over 220 productions since its founding in 1976.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/act-two-ushering-in-new-era.html|title=ACT TWO: Ushering In A New Era|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano serves as the theatre's Founding Producing Artistic Director. Along with directing [[Latino theatre in the United States|Latino theatre]], Medrano is an accomplished actor. He received the [[Helen Hayes Award]] for Outstanding Lead Actor for his role as Molina in [[Kiss of the Spider Woman (novel)|El Beso de la Mujer Arana]] in 1994. Medrano's work with the Gala Hispanic Theatre has earned international acclaim. For his dedication to promoting Spanish culture in the [[United States]], Medrano was bestowed the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic|Order of Queen Isabella]] by [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Carlos I]], former King of [[Spain]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/hugo-medrano.html|title=Hugo Medrano|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHugo Medrano lived in Argentina for much of his early life. He attended Escuela de Teatro de La Plata and graduated with a Bachelor's degree in Theatre.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Shortly after graduation, Medrano fled [[political violence]] as a result of Argentina's [[Dirty War]] which targeted [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] political dissidents.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mdtheatreguide.com/2011/10/an-interview-with-gala-hispanic-theatres-hugo-medrano/|title=An Interview with GALA Hispanic Theatre\u2019s Hugo Medrano|last=Matema|first=ZSun-nee|date=2011-10-08|website=Maryland Theatre Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> He reported that many of his friends were some of the students, intellectuals, and artists who [[Forced disappearance#Argentina|disappeared]] as a result of the war. These experiences inspired the political themes of Medrano's early work.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nMedrano continued his studies in Spain at the [[:es:Teatro Estudio de Madrid|Teatro Estudio de Madrid]]. He lived and performed in Spain for five years before immigrating to the United States.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nHugo Medrano's career in the United States began at Teatro Doble, a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] children's theatre located in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, most of his notable work was done with the GALA Hispanic Theatre. GALA stands for Grupo de Artistas Latino Americanos.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://wamu.org/story/13/09/13/gala_hispanic_brings_spanish_language_theater_to_dc_for_nearly_40_years/|title=Gala Hispanic Brings Spanish-Language Theater To D.C. For Nearly 40 Years|website=WAMU|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano co-founded this theatre in 1976 to deliver quality plays to the growing Spanish-speaking community of Washington. In its early years, the GALA Hispanic Theatre performed in a townhouse in the multicultural [[Adams Morgan]] neighborhood of the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/blog-post/hugo-and-rebecca-medrano-and-hispanic-theater|title=Hugo and Rebecca Medrano and Hispanic Theater|date=2017-10-25|website=Wilson Center|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Hugo Medrano produced and directed the group's first production, [[:es:La fiaca (obra de teatro)|La Fiaca]] by [[:es:Ricardo Talesnik|Ricardo Talesnik]], which received recognition by the [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]. Medrano would go on to direct, produce, and act in a multitude of successful productions over the next 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/04/production-history.html|title=Production History|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BxU-f08JvfaYS1BDLTZPYmRhdVE/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=Production History June 2016.pdf|website=Google Docs|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAs a theatre director at GALA, Hugo Medrano faced challenges concerning the bilingual nature of his productions. To appeal to both Spanish-speaking and English-speaking audiences, Medrano would often present two different productions of the same play, an English version and a Spanish version.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In some cases, this would require two different actors, [[Costume coordination|costumes]], or directors to perform these productions. Medrano found this approach to be inefficient, and the GALA Hispanic Theatre subsequently transitioned to producing plays in Spanish and providing English subtitles or headphone translations to the audience.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nMoving the GALA Hispanic Theatre to a permanent home in the [[Tivoli Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Tivoli Theatre]] of [[Columbia Heights, Washington, D.C.|Columbia Heights]] was an important moment in Hugo Medrano's career. The Tivoli Theatre was built in 1924 and quickly became a city landmark as both a theatre and a cinema.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.galatheatre.org/2016/05/history-of-tivoli-theatre.html|title=The Venue - History of Tivoli Theatre|website=GALA Theatre|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> The theatre was abandoned in 1976 but was restored with the help of a $4 million fundraising campaign started by Hugo Medrano and others.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> In 2005, the GALA Hispanic Theatre officially moved into the Tivoli Theatre and Medrano began to work on new projects. With the help of his wife, Hugo Medrano created the National Center for Latino Performing Arts and has expanded GALA's focus to include concerts, dance, film, and other arts.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Notable productions ==\n\n===''In the Heights''===\n''[[In the Heights]]'' is a [[Tony Award]] winning broadway musical which featured music and lyrics by [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]. In 2017, Hugo Medrano and the GALA Hispanic Theatre hosted the first all Spanish version of the production in the United States. The musical is usually performed in [[Spanglish]], a mix of Spanish and English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/04/18/lin-manuel-miranda-in-the-heights-spanish-premiere-gala-theatre/|title=An All-Spanish Version of Lin-Manuel Miranda's \"In the Heights\" Has Its US Premiere at DC's GALA Hispanic Theatre|date=2017-04-18|website=Washingtonian|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nHugo Medrano was recognized as a \"Visionary\" by the Mayor's Arts Awards in 2014. He also received an Immigrant Achievement Award from the [[American Immigration Council]] in 2014. In 2010, both Hugo Medrano and his wife Rebecca Read Medrano were named Washingtonians of the Year by the [[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]] magazine.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medrano, Hugo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Argentine emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Argentine descent]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American male actors]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Medrano"}
